# Project Context: Trucking Pay Wizard

A standalone desktop tool that processes trucking income documents for legal staff. Staff drop documents into a working folder, run the pipeline, and receive a combined PDF report and CSV spreadsheet with cross-referenced extracted values.

## Pipeline

```
Ingestion → OCR → Extraction (+ Classification) → Validation → Report Assembly
```

- Per-document stages (Ingestion through Validation) are cacheable — only new/unprocessed documents re-run.
- Report Assembly always rebuilds from the full set of cached results.
- OCR provider: **Azure Document Intelligence** (credentials via `.env`).
- Extraction provider: **Anthropic API** (Claude Haiku). OCR text is PII-sanitized before it leaves the machine.
- The extraction step also **classifies** each document as a payment document or not (`is_payment_document` on `DocumentExtractionResult`), erring toward "payment document" when uncertain. Non-payment documents are excluded from the combined PDF but still listed (grayed out) in the spreadsheet.

## Session Model

```
working-folder/
  ├── <source documents>     # staff-provided, never modified
  ├── .cache/                # per-document JSON results (keyed by content hash + version)
  ├── combined_report.pdf    # generated output
  └── extracted_data.csv     # generated output
```

The folder *is* the session — no database, no server.

## Scope

**Active:** folder-based batch processing, OCR, field extraction (gross pay, net pay, dates), document classification (payment vs. non-payment), validation, report assembly, desktop GUI, standalone executable packaging.

**Not yet active:** template detection. Documents are classified as payment or non-payment, but specific document templates are not yet auto-detected.

## Delivery

Ships as a standalone **Windows** executable. All end users (downtime claims staff) are on Windows. The GUI calls into the pipeline; the pipeline never imports from the GUI.

## Developer Environment

All development tasks — pytest, GUI, packaging — use **PowerShell (Windows)**. Always use PowerShell syntax: `$env:VAR`, `.venv\Scripts\activate`, `New-Item`, `Copy-Item`.

Code uses `pathlib.Path` throughout so it stays platform-neutral, but builds and end-user deployment target Windows only.
